#. (itstool) path: chapter/title
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:8
msgid "VM Guest Clock Settings"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: abstract/para
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:11
msgid ""
"Keeping the correct time in a VM Guest is one of the more difficult aspects "
"of virtualization. Keeping the correct time is especially important for "
"network applications and is also a prerequisite to do a live migration of a "
"VM Guest."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: tip/title
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:23
msgid "Timekeeping on the VM Host Server"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: tip/para
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:24
msgid ""
"It is strongly recommended to ensure the VM Host Server keeps the correct "
"time as well, for example, by using NTP (see <xref linkend=\"cha.ntp\"/> for "
"more information)."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/title
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:31
msgid "KVM: Using <systemitem>kvm_clock</systemitem>"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:33
msgid ""
"KVM provides a paravirtualized clock which is supported via the "
"<systemitem>kvm_clock</systemitem> driver. It is strongly recommended to use "
"<systemitem>kvm_clock</systemitem>."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:39
msgid ""
"Use the following command inside a VM Guest running Linux to check whether "
"the driver <systemitem>kvm_clock</systemitem> has been loaded:"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/screen
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:44
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<prompt>tux &gt; </prompt><command>sudo</command> dmesg | grep kvm-clock\n"
"[    0.000000] kvm-clock: cpu 0, msr 0:7d3a81, boot clock\n"
"[    0.000000] kvm-clock: cpu 0, msr 0:1206a81, primary cpu clock\n"
"[    0.012000] kvm-clock: cpu 1, msr 0:1306a81, secondary cpu clock\n"
"[    0.160082] Switching to clocksource kvm-clock"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:50
msgid ""
"To check which clock source is currently used, run the following command in "
"the VM Guest. It should output <literal>kvm-clock</literal>:"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/screen
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "<prompt>tux &gt; </prompt>cat /sys/devices/system/clocksource/clocksource0/current_clocksource"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: important/title
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:58
msgid "<literal>kvm-clock</literal> and NTP"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: important/para
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:60
msgid ""
"When using <literal>kvm-clock</literal>, it is recommended to use NTP in the "
"VM Guest, as well. Using NTP on the VM Host Server is also recommended."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect2/title
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:67
msgid "Other Timekeeping Methods"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect2/para
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:68
msgid ""
"The paravirtualized <literal>kvm-clock</literal> is currently not for "
"Windows* operating systems. For Windows*, use the <literal>Windows Time "
"Service Tools</literal> for time synchronization (see <link xlink:href="
"\"http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/cc773263%28WS.10%29.aspx\"/> "
"for more information)."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/title
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:78
msgid "Xen Virtual Machine Clock Settings"
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:80
msgid ""
"With Xen 4, the independent wallclock setting <filename>/proc/sys/xen/"
"independent_wallclock</filename> used for time synchronization between Xen "
"host and guest was removed. A new configuration option <option>tsc_mode</"
"option> was introduced. It specifies a method of utilizing the "
"<emphasis>timestamp counter</emphasis> to synchronize the guest time with "
"the Xen server. Its default value '0' handles the vast majority of hardware "
"and software environments."
msgstr ""

#. (itstool) path: sect1/para
#: xml/vt_clocksettings.xml:90
msgid ""
"For more details on <option>tsc_mode</option>, see the <literal>xen-tscmode</"
"literal> manual page (<command>man 7 xen-tscmode</command>)."
msgstr ""
